A bag only contains red marbles, blue marbles and yellow marbles. The probability of picking a red marble is $2/5$. There are nine yellow marbles. The probability of picking a blue marble is three times as likely as picking a yellow marble. Work out the total number of marbles in the bag. You must show your working.
</span>
<div class="model_answer">
Let the number of yellow marbles be $y$, the number of blue marbles be $b$, and the number of red marbles be $r$. Let the total number of marbles be $n$.
<br>
We are given that $y = 9$.
<br>
The probability of picking a red marble is $\frac{2}{5}$.
<br>
The probability of picking a blue marble is three times as likely as picking a yellow marble.
<br>
So, $b = 3y = 3 \times 9 = 27$. <span class="marking-code">[M2]</span>
<br>
The probability of picking a yellow marble is $\frac{9}{n}$.
<br>
The probability of picking a blue marble is $\frac{27}{n}$.
<br>
The probability of picking a red marble is $\frac{r}{n} = \frac{2}{5}$.
<br>
The sum of the probabilities of picking a red, blue, or yellow marble is 1.
<br>
$\frac{2}{5} + \frac{9}{n} + \frac{27}{n} = 1$ <span class="marking-code">[M3]</span>
<br>
$\frac{2}{5} + \frac{36}{n} = 1$
<br>
$\frac{36}{n} = 1 - \frac{2}{5} = \frac{3}{5}$
<br>
$n = \frac{36 \times 5}{3} = 12 \times 5 = 60$ <span class="marking-code">[M4]</span>
<br>
The number of red marbles is $\frac{2}{5} \times 60 = 24$. <span class="marking-code">[B2]</span>
<br>
Total number of marbles in the bag is $60$.
<br>
$n = 60$
<span class="marking-code">[A1]</span>
